                  <t:persName xml:lang="gez" xml:id="n1" type="birth">ኪዳነ፡ ወልድ፡ ክፍሌ፡</t:persName>
               <t:persName xml:lang="gez" corresp="#n1" type="normalized">Kidāna Wald Kǝfle</t:persName>
             
                  
               <t:persName>
                  <t:roleName type="title">ʾalaqā</t:roleName>
               </t:persName>
                  
                  <t:nationality type="Ethiopia"/>
                  <t:faith type="EOTC"/>
                  
                  
                  <t:occupation type="literary"> scholar</t:occupation>
               <t:birth notBefore="1869" notAfter="1872"/>
                  
                  
               <t:floruit notBefore="1892" notAfter="1944">He was a celebrated Ethiopian theologian, grammarian and lexicographer. 
                  Kidāna Wald Kǝfle was born to a family of respected ecclesiastics. While still very young, he
                  was taught calligraphy by his grandfather <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS10276Yawnatu">
                     <t:roleName type="title">mamhǝr</t:roleName>
                  </t:persName>. 
                  At the age of 20 he left for <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC3957Jerusa">Jerusalem</t:placeName>,  in <t:date>1890</t:date>, where he lived for 30 years. 
                  In <t:placeName ref="https://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q1218">Jerusalem</t:placeName>, Kidāna Wald Kǝfle
                  was earning a  living by copying manuscripts.  In <t:placeName ref="https://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q1218">Jerusalem</t:placeName>
                  he also learned traditional exegesis (ʾAndǝmtā) from a renowned traditional scholar <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS5907KeflaGi">Kǝfla Giyorgis</t:persName>. 
                 Kidāna Wald Kǝfle remained with <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS5907KeflaGi">Kǝfla Giyorgis</t:persName> until 
                  the later's death in <t:date>1908</t:date>. After he returned to <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC3010Ethiop">Ethiopia</t:placeName> in <t:date>1920</t:date>, 
                  he prepared several Gǝʿǝz texts with their Amharic commentaries for the publication. </t:floruit>
               <t:death when="1944"/>
                  
                  
               </t:person>
               
               
         </t:listPerson>
         
         
